ied social theoretical foundation. As the first generation of critical theorists knew, thought itself can be reified, our imaginations debased, and our desires artificially induced. We need to think beyond recognition and embrace a more potent and aggressive form of social critique, true to the founding spirit of the Frankfurt School.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCritical theory. 0aFrankfurt school of sociology. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Movements / Critical Theory.2bisacsh  aAxel Honneth.  aCritical Theory.  aErich Fromm.  aHerbert Marcuse.  aNeo-Idealism.  aOne Dimensionality.  aPathological Normalcy.  aRecognition.  aSocial Pathology.  aSocial research.1 aHarris, Neal, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2022 eBook-Packagez978311128144540uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152615474340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526154743423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526154743/original  a978-3-11-128144-5  Manchester University Press 2022 eBook-Packageb2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles